quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to fix the paragraph to 100px from the top and 50px from the left:
[!raw!]
p {
   {0}: fixed;
   {1}: 50px;
   {2}: 100px;
}

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Fixed Positioning[/h1]

An element with a fixed position is positioned relative to the browser window, and will not move even if the window is scrolled.
The position can be specified using one or more of the properties [b]top[/b], [b]right[/b], [b]bottom[/b], and [b]left[/b]. 
In the example below, the paragraph is fixed to 30px from the top and 5px from the right. 

[b]The CSS:[/b][code format="css" codeId="568"]p.position_fixed {
   [b]position: fixed;[/b]
   top: 30px;
   right: 5px;
   color: red;
}[/code]
[b]Result:[/b] [img id="3012" width="100%"]  
[note]Fixed positioned elements are removed from the normal flow. The document and other elements behave like the fixed positioned element does not exist.
Fixed positioned elements can overlap other elements.[/note]

[h1]Relative Positioning[/h1]

A relative positioned element is positioned relative to its normal position. 
The properties [b]top[/b], [b]right[/b], [b]bottom[/b], and [b]left [/b]can be used to specify how the rendered box will be shifted. 

[b]The CSS:[/b][code format="css" codeId="569"]p {
   width: 350px;
   border: 1px black solid;
   [b]position: fixed;[/b]
}
span {
   background: green;
   color:white;
  [b] position: relative[/b];
   [b]top[/b]: 150px;
   [b]left[/b]: 50px;
}[/code]
[b]Result:[/b][img id="2996" width="100%"]  
The content of relatively positioned elements can be moved and overlap other elements, but the reserved space for the element is still preserved in the normal flow.
[note]This value cannot be used for [b]table cells[/b], [b]columns[/b], [b]column groups[/b], [b]rows[/b], [b]row groups[/b], or [b]captions[/b].[/note]
[h1]Absolute Positioning[/h1]
An absolute position element is positioned relative to the first parent element that has a position other than static. If no such element is found, the containing block is <html>.

Absolutely positioned elements are removed from the normal flow. The document and other elements behave like the absolutely positioned element does not exist.
[note]Absolutely positioned elements can overlap other elements.[/note]
